captions: Image describes The image features a man wearing a blue and white striped shirt, sitting in front of a wall. He appears to be an older man with a beard and mustache. The man is wearing a tie, which is visible in the lower part of the image. The overall color scheme of the image is predominantly blue and white, with the man's shirt and tie being the main sources of these colors. and the video's audio describes America's longest war, the so-called forever war may actually be ending, may. Yesterday in Doha representatives of the United States and the Taliban signed the agreement for bringing peace to Afghanistan. The document sets a 14-month window for the U.S. to withdraw its troops. It also calls for the release of up to 5,000 Taliban prisoners. On the other side, the Taliban promises to prevent terror groups from using Afghanistan as a base to threaten the United States and its allies. There is one absolutely critical party to any Afghan peace who was in at the signing, the president of Afghanistan, Ashraf Ghani. He may not have been in Doha, but he joins me now from Kabul. Welcome, Mr. President. It's a pleasure to be with you. The day before the signing, the head of the Taliban's media operation said, this is a defeat, a defeat for the arrogance of the White House in the face of the White Turban. Is it a defeat for America? No, it's not. The narrative is false because there's been no military defeat. It's a political decision to end the war politically. Not only is the United States not defeated, the Afghan security forces are at their best and in the last seven months it's been Taliban that it's been losing. But our conviction that the war must end politically is what is driven this process forward. The victors of the war are no one. The victors of the peace are going to be the people of Afghanistan. We need to drop that kind of arrogant language and move forward to discuss our differences in the ways where we can come together as a United country, a United people, in a United nation. The 5,000 prisoners who have been mentioned, as you have pointed out, are not going to be released by the United States. They are under your authority. The authority of the Afghan government. Now, I remember when the United States released five Afghan prisoners from Guantanamo. This was an exchange for Bobur Gaur. There was an outcry, particularly among the Republican Party. Now, a Republican president is asking you to release 5,000 Taliban prisoners of war. Before you even start the talks with the Taliban, is that going to happen? President Trump is not asking me to release these people. We have not made a commitment to release them. It's a sovereign Afghan decision. We will discuss the question of prisoners as part of a peace still, which is to be comprehensive, which is to discuss. The wording that is used there is that the United States would facilitate with made it very clear to Ambassador Khalid Zad that the political capital in the consensus in the country that would be necessary for such a major step does not exist today. We need to see that significant issues, a permanent ceasefire discussion of the special relationship of Taliban to the countries that provide them sanctuary, especially Pakistan. Their relationship with all terrorist organizations, not just al-Qaeda, their relationship with drug cartels and most fundamentally the basic rights of the people of Afghanistan, the place of our security forces and our civilian administration, or all discussed. It is very clearly conveyed to them that they cannot put pre-conditions. Just technically, it's not possible to release 5,000 prisoners. It's a pain-staking process. Each person needs to be checked and in return for what we need to understand that the of one people have to see. Continuous commitment, not a sense of false claims of victory because all our forces and our government capabilities are intact.
